This C function allocates a 2-D image buffer from user-supplied dimensions. Find any integer security issues and provide the secure version.

```c
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <stdint.h>

void* alloc_image(int width, int height, int channels) {
    size_t size = width * height * channels;  /* may overflow */
    return malloc(size);
}
```

## Vulnerability: CWE-190 Integer Overflow → CWE-122 Heap Buffer Overflow

### Exploit path
`width * height * channels` is computed in **`int`** arithmetic. If an attacker passes `width=32768, height=32768, channels=4`, the product is `4,294,967,296`, which wraps to `0` in 32-bit signed arithmetic (undefined behaviour under ISO C; in practice wraps on x86). `malloc(0)` returns a tiny-or-NULL pointer. Subsequent pixel writes walk far beyond the allocation — heap overflow. This class of bug underlies CVE-2021-3009 (libpng), CVE-2019-11048 (PHP), and others.

CERT C INT32-C: *Ensure that operations on signed integers do not result in overflow.*
CERT C INT30-C: *Ensure that unsigned integer operations do not wrap.*

### NEVER DO THIS
```c
size_t size = width * height * channels;  // int * int * int → int overflow → wrong size
```

### Fixed — validated inputs, overflow-safe multiply, size cap
```c
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <stdint.h>
#include <stdio.h>

#define IMAGE_DIM_MAX   65536          /* reject absurd dimensions */
#define IMAGE_CHAN_MAX  4
#define IMAGE_BYTES_MAX (1ULL << 30)   /* 1 GiB hard cap */

/*
 * Multiply two size_t values checking for overflow.
 * Returns 1 on overflow (product undefined), 0 on success.
 * Uses __builtin_mul_overflow (GCC/Clang) when available;
 * falls back to division check otherwise.
 */
static int safe_mul(size_t a, size_t b, size_t *result) {
#if defined(__GNUC__) || defined(__clang__)
    return __builtin_mul_overflow(a, b, result);
#else
    if (b != 0 && a > SIZE_MAX / b) return 1;   /* would overflow */
    *result = a * b;
    return 0;
#endif
}

void* alloc_image(int width, int height, int channels) {
    /* ── 1. Reject negative or out-of-range inputs */
    if (width  <= 0 || width  > IMAGE_DIM_MAX ||
        height <= 0 || height > IMAGE_DIM_MAX ||
        channels <= 0 || channels > IMAGE_CHAN_MAX) {
        fprintf(stderr, "alloc_image: invalid dimensions %dx%dx%d\n",
                width, height, channels);
        return NULL;
    }

    /* ── 2. Promote to size_t BEFORE any multiplication */
    size_t w = (size_t)width;
    size_t h = (size_t)height;
    size_t c = (size_t)channels;

    /* ── 3. Overflow-safe multiply chain */
    size_t row_bytes, total;
    if (safe_mul(w, c, &row_bytes) || safe_mul(row_bytes, h, &total)) {
        fprintf(stderr, "alloc_image: dimension product overflows size_t\n");
        return NULL;
    }

    /* ── 4. Hard cap: refuse absurdly large allocations */
    if (total > IMAGE_BYTES_MAX) {
        fprintf(stderr, "alloc_image: %zu bytes exceeds 1 GiB cap\n", total);
        return NULL;
    }

    /* ── 5. Check malloc success */
    void *buf = malloc(total);
    if (!buf) {
        perror("malloc");
    }
    return buf;
}
```

### Defence summary
| Layer | Mechanism |
|---|---|
| Negative/zero inputs | Explicit range check before any arithmetic |
| Promote early | Cast to `size_t` before multiplying — no signed intermediate |
| Overflow-safe multiply | `__builtin_mul_overflow` or division-based check |
| Hard cap | Reject plausible-but-dangerous allocations above 1 GiB |
| malloc NULL check | Never assume allocation succeeded |

**References:** CERT C INT30-C, INT32-C, MEM04-C; CWE-190, CWE-122; MISRA C:2025 Rule 10.1.

