## Why Rust Eliminates Memory Safety Bugs C++ Can't Prevent at Compile Time

### Scenario: shared mutable buffer updated from two threads

---

### C++ — VULNERABLE (CWE-362 Race Condition + CWE-416 potential UAF)
```cpp
// BAD: two threads write to shared vector — data race → UB
#include <thread>
#include <vector>
#include <cstdio>

std::vector<int> g_buf;

void producer(int val) {
    g_buf.push_back(val);   // realloc inside push_back races with reader
}

int main() {
    std::thread t1(producer, 1);
    std::thread t2(producer, 2);
    t1.join(); t2.join();
    // g_buf may be heap-corrupted; iterator from t1 dangling after t2 realloc
    for (int v : g_buf) printf("%d\n", v);
}
// C++ COMPILER ACCEPTS THIS — no diagnostic, no error.
// ThreadSanitizer detects it at runtime only.
```

---

### C++ — FIXED with `std::mutex` (correct but fragile)
```cpp
#include <thread>
#include <vector>
#include <mutex>
#include <cstdio>

std::vector<int> g_buf;
std::mutex       g_mu;

void producer(int val) {
    std::lock_guard<std::mutex> lock(g_mu);  // RAII lock
    g_buf.push_back(val);   // safe while locked
}   // lock released here

int main() {
    std::thread t1(producer, 1);
    std::thread t2(producer, 2);
    t1.join(); t2.join();
    // Still need lock to read safely:
    std::lock_guard<std::mutex> lock(g_mu);
    for (int v : g_buf) printf("%d\n", v);
}
// Correct — but NOTHING prevents a programmer from forgetting the lock_guard
// on any future access. C++ provides no compile-time enforcement.
```

---

### Rust — COMPILER ENFORCES SAFETY STATICALLY
```rust
// Rust: shared mutable access requires Arc<Mutex<T>> — the type system
// makes it impossible to access the Vec without holding the lock.

use std::sync::{Arc, Mutex};
use std::thread;

fn main() {
    // Arc = atomic reference count (shared ownership across threads)
    // Mutex<Vec<i32>> = the Vec is only accessible through the Mutex
    let buf: Arc<Mutex<Vec<i32>>> = Arc::new(Mutex::new(Vec::new()));

    let handles: Vec<_> = (1..=2).map(|val| {
        let buf = Arc::clone(&buf);   // clone the Arc, not the Vec
        thread::spawn(move || {
            // .lock() blocks until the Mutex is available;
            // returns MutexGuard<Vec<i32>> — a temporary that holds the lock.
            let mut guard = buf.lock().unwrap();
            guard.push(val);
            // guard drops here → mutex released automatically (RAII)
        })
    }).collect();

    for h in handles { h.join().unwrap(); }

    // To read, must also lock:
    let guard = buf.lock().unwrap();
    for v in guard.iter() { println!("{v}"); }
}

// ── What the Rust compiler STATICALLY rejects:
// let raw: &Vec<i32> = &*buf.lock().unwrap();
// drop(buf);          // ← compile error: 'raw' borrows 'buf' which is moved
// println!("{}", raw[0]);  // use after move — rejected at compile time
//
// Attempting to share &mut Vec<i32> across threads without Arc<Mutex>:
// thread::spawn(|| buf.push(3));  // ← error[E0277]: Vec<i32> is not Send
//                                  //   cannot be sent to another thread safely
```

### Why the Rust compiler can guarantee what C++ cannot
| Guarantee | C++ mechanism | Enforced? | Rust mechanism | Enforced? |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| Mutual exclusion on shared data | `std::mutex` (manual) | Runtime only | `Mutex<T>` wraps data — impossible to access without lock | Compile time |
| No use-after-free | Smart pointers (discipline) | Runtime only | Ownership + borrow checker | Compile time |
| No data races | `lock_guard` (discipline) | Runtime only | `Send`/`Sync` trait bounds | Compile time |
| No dangling references | `unique_ptr` (discipline) | Runtime only | Lifetimes | Compile time |

### Security implication
Microsoft and Google have independently reported that ~70% of their memory-safety CVEs come from C/C++ bugs that Rust's type system would reject at compile time. Moving security-critical code to Rust (or applying MISRA C:2025 + CERT C strictly in C) eliminates an entire vulnerability class without runtime overhead — Rust's borrow checker operates at zero runtime cost.

**References:** CERT C++ CON50-CPP, MEM50-CPP; CWE-362, CWE-416; MISRA C:2025 Rule 22.5; NSA 'Software Memory Safety' guidance 2023; Rust Reference — Send and Sync traits.

